data.content:
Yes! For simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` — it's simpler and strongly typed:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need complex types that `[DataRow]` can't handle (it only supports compile-time constants), MSTest v3.4+ supports **generic `DynamicData`** to avoid `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Summary:** Use `[DataRow]` for simple constants (preferred). Use generic `DynamicData<T>` with tuples when you need computed/complex test data — you get type safety and no `object[]` boxing.
